ies lead to full participation but require large financial transfers we present a simple model to analyze this trade off between adverse selection and infra marginal transfers we find that increasing the scale of voluntary programs both improves efficiency and reduces transfers we show that discounting paying less than full value for offsets is inefficient and cannot be used to reduce the fraction of offsets that are spurious while setting stringent baselines generally can both approaches reduce the cost to the offsets buyer the effects of two popular policy options are less favorable than many believe limiting the number of offsets that can be one for one exchanged with permits in a cap and trade system will lower the offset price but also quality trading ratios between offsets and allowances have ambiguous environmental effects if the cap is not properly adjusted this paper frames the issues in terms of avoiding deforestation but the results are applicable to any voluntary offset program download pdf+ complete modified march 2011 pdf wp_102_benthem_and_kerr_bigger pdf 919.8 kb parent research climate change policy topics cap and trade mechanism deforestation energy environment and climate change sustainable development search publications everything publications of interest adverse selection in an opt in emissions trading program the case of sectoral crediting for transportation adam millard ball program on energy and sustainable development 2010 pdf+ cover making carbon offsets work in the developing world lessons from the chinese wind controversy gang he richard k morse program on energy and sustainable development working paper 90 2010 pdf+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 724 1714 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
